window.CISA = window.CISA || {}; CISA.reading = CISA.reading || {};
CISA.reading[2] = [{"heading":"Laws, Regulations, and Industry Standards","body":"<p><span class='keyterm'>Domain 2 — Governance and Management of IT</span> is roughly 18% of the CISA exam, and every item is written from one seat: the <span class='keyterm'>independent IS auditor</span>. You are not the CIO, the risk officer, or the general counsel. Your job is to evaluate whether the enterprise has established a governance and management framework that keeps IT aligned with business objectives, and whether that framework actually operates. Governance is about direction, oversight, and accountability; management is about planning, building, running, and monitoring within that direction. The exam rewards answers that reflect independence, evidence, and a control mindset — the auditor who asks \"show me the approved policy, the committee minutes, the risk register entry\" over the auditor impressed by activity. Hold that frame through all eleven sections.</p><p>The first thing an enterprise must know is which external rules bind it, because compliance obligations are inputs to governance, risk, and control design. The auditor begins by evaluating whether management maintains a <span class='keyterm'>legal and regulatory register</span> — a documented inventory of the laws, regulations, and contractual obligations that apply, mapped to the systems, processes, and controls that satisfy them. Without such a register, compliance is a matter of hope rather than design, and the auditor cannot conclude that obligations are being met.</p><h3>Major Laws and Regulations the Exam Expects</h3><p>Several instruments recur on the exam, and the auditor must know what each demands and what evidence demonstrates compliance. The <span class='keyterm'>Sarbanes-Oxley Act (SOX)</span> — U.S. legislation for public companies — makes management responsible for the effectiveness of internal control over financial reporting (ICFR). For IT, this drives general controls over the applications and infrastructure that produce financial statements: access management, change management, and IT operations. The auditor evaluates whether IT general controls (ITGCs) supporting financial systems are designed and operating, because a control weakness there undermines assurance over the numbers. The <span class='keyterm'>General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR)</span> — the EU privacy law — grants data subjects rights, requires a lawful basis for processing, mandates breach notification (generally within 72 hours to the supervisory authority), and can impose fines up to 4% of global annual turnover. <span class='keyterm'>HIPAA</span> protects U.S. health information through Privacy, Security, and Breach Notification Rules. The <span class='keyterm'>Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard (PCI DSS)</span> is a contractual standard, not a law, imposed by the card brands on any entity that stores, processes, or transmits cardholder data; it prescribes specific controls and requires periodic validation. <span class='keyterm'>ISO/IEC 27001</span> is a voluntary but certifiable standard specifying requirements for an information security management system (ISMS).</p><table><thead><tr><th>Instrument</th><th>Type</th><th>Core obligation</th><th>Evidence the auditor seeks</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>SOX (§302/§404)</td><td>Law (US public co.)</td><td>Effective ICFR; ITGCs over financial systems</td><td>Control matrices, access reviews, change tickets, management assertion</td></tr><tr><td>GDPR</td><td>Regulation (EU)</td><td>Lawful basis, data-subject rights, 72-hour breach notice</td><td>Records of processing, DPIAs, consent logs, breach register</td></tr><tr><td>HIPAA</td><td>Law (US health)</td><td>Safeguard PHI (Privacy/Security/Breach rules)</td><td>Risk analysis, BAAs, access controls, encryption evidence</td></tr><tr><td>PCI DSS</td><td>Contractual standard</td><td>Protect cardholder data via prescribed controls</td><td>ROC/SAQ, segmentation tests, quarterly scans, ASV reports</td></tr><tr><td>ISO/IEC 27001</td><td>Voluntary standard</td><td>Operate a risk-based ISMS</td><td>Statement of Applicability, risk treatment plan, certificate</td></tr></tbody></table><p>Two distinctions matter for exam items. First, a <span class='keyterm'>law or regulation</span> is imposed by a government and carries legal penalties, whereas a <span class='keyterm'>standard</span> (ISO, PCI DSS, NIST) is a documented benchmark that may be voluntary or contractual. Confusing PCI DSS for a law, or treating ISO 27001 certification as a legal requirement, is a classic trap. Second, compliance is not a control objective in itself — it is a driver. The auditor evaluates whether management translated each obligation into specific, owned, testable controls.</p><h3>How the Auditor Assesses Compliance</h3><p>Assessing compliance is a repeatable procedure. The auditor (1) confirms a current inventory of applicable requirements exists and is maintained as laws change; (2) verifies each requirement is mapped to a responsible owner and to the control(s) that satisfy it; (3) tests whether those controls are designed appropriately and operating effectively over the period; and (4) evaluates how management monitors ongoing compliance and remediates gaps. A frequent finding is that the organization treats compliance as a point-in-time certification exercise rather than a continuous obligation, so controls decay between assessments. The auditor also watches for <span class='keyterm'>conflicting or overlapping requirements</span> across jurisdictions — a multinational may face GDPR, sector rules, and local data-residency laws simultaneously — and evaluates whether management has reconciled them rather than satisfying one while breaching another.</p><p>Because obligations change, the register cannot be static. The auditor evaluates the process that keeps it current: who monitors legislative and regulatory developments, how new or amended requirements are assessed for impact, and how changes flow into control updates. A mature function has a named owner (often legal, compliance, or a dedicated regulatory-affairs role) and a documented cadence for horizon-scanning. The auditor asks how the last significant regulatory change was identified and absorbed; if management cannot answer, the register is likely stale. Contractual obligations belong in the same inventory — client security schedules, data-processing agreements, and regulator undertakings impose requirements just as binding as statute, and they are frequently overlooked because they live in procurement or legal files rather than the compliance system.</p><h3>Standards and Frameworks as Criteria</h3><p>Beyond the marquee laws, the auditor encounters a family of industry standards and frameworks that function as recognized criteria. The <span class='keyterm'>NIST Cybersecurity Framework</span> and the <span class='keyterm'>NIST SP 800-53</span> control catalog are widely used, especially by U.S. federal-facing organizations. The <span class='keyterm'>ISO/IEC 27000 series</span> extends 27001 with implementation guidance (27002) and sector variants. <span class='keyterm'>COBIT</span> supplies governance and management objectives. The important audit point is that a standard is a benchmark the enterprise chooses to adopt or is contractually required to follow; adopting one does not by itself satisfy law, and certification against one is evidence of a management system's existence, not a guarantee that every legal obligation is met. The auditor treats these frameworks as the measuring stick for \"good practice\" while keeping the distinction between voluntary adoption and legal mandate sharp, because exam stems deliberately blur it. A related concept is a <span class='keyterm'>generally accepted framework</span>: choosing a recognized, published standard is itself a control, because it demonstrates due care and provides an objective basis for assessment rather than management's private opinion of what \"adequate\" means.</p><p>The auditor must remain independent even when management asserts compliance. An attestation from legal or a vendor's certificate is corroborating evidence, not proof of operating effectiveness in the client's environment. For PCI DSS in particular, the auditor should understand that a passing self-assessment questionnaire (SAQ) reflects management's representations; independent validation may still be warranted. A vendor's SOC 2 report or ISO certificate covers the vendor's own environment, a defined scope, and a defined period — the auditor reads the scope, the exceptions, and the complementary user-entity controls before relying on it. The overarching message for the exam: the auditor evaluates whether compliance is <em>engineered into the control environment and monitored</em>, not merely claimed.</p><p>The auditor should also be clear about the difference between a <span class='keyterm'>compliance audit</span> and a controls audit. A compliance audit measures conformity to an external requirement — a law, regulation, standard, or contract — and answers \"does the organization meet this obligation?\" A controls audit evaluates whether internal controls achieve their objectives regardless of any external mandate. The two overlap but are not identical: an organization can be technically compliant with a checklist yet still carry unmanaged risk, and it can operate strong controls while breaching a specific legal formality. On the exam, when a stem describes a requirement imposed by an outside body and asks what the audit should assess, the answer usually centers on whether the organization has identified the requirement, mapped it to controls, and can demonstrate conformity with evidence. Where the auditor's own independence is in question — for instance, if the audit team helped design the very compliance program it is now assessing — that self-review threat must be disclosed and managed, because assurance over compliance means nothing if the assessor is not objective. The auditor's deliverable is an evidence-based conclusion on whether obligations are identified, controlled, monitored, and demonstrably met, together with findings where they are not, ranked by the severity of the exposure each gap creates for the enterprise. In every case the conclusion rests on evidence gathered independently, not on management's word that all is well.</p><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div><p>Watch for the law-versus-standard distinction. <b>PCI DSS</b> is a contractual standard from the card brands, <b>not</b> a law; <b>ISO/IEC 27001</b> is a voluntary certifiable standard, not a legal mandate. <b>SOX</b> and <b>GDPR</b> are law. When a stem says an organization is \"required by regulation,\" verify the instrument actually is a regulation before choosing it.</p></div><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div><p>An IS auditor finds the company completed an ISO 27001 audit two years ago but cannot produce a current list of the laws and regulations that apply to its lines of business. The most significant concern is not the age of the certificate — it is the <b>absence of a maintained legal/regulatory inventory mapped to controls</b>. Without it, management cannot demonstrate that changing obligations are identified and satisfied, so compliance cannot be relied upon.</p></div>"},
{"heading":"Organizational Structure, IT Governance, and IT Strategy","body":"<p><span class='keyterm'>IT governance</span> is the system by which the enterprise directs and controls IT so that IT sustains and extends the organization's strategy and objectives. It is a subset of enterprise governance and is ultimately the responsibility of the <span class='keyterm'>board of directors</span>. The auditor's central question in this domain is whether the board and executive management have established structures, processes, and accountability that keep IT investments aligned with business goals and risk within appetite — and whether those structures function in practice or exist only on an org chart.</p><h3>Governance versus Management</h3><p>The single most important conceptual distinction in this domain is <span class='keyterm'>governance versus management</span>. In <span class='keyterm'>COBIT 2019</span>, governance ensures stakeholder needs are evaluated to determine objectives, sets direction through prioritization and decision-making, and monitors performance and compliance — summarized as <span class='keyterm'>EDM (Evaluate, Direct, Monitor)</span>, and it is the board's accountability. Management plans, builds, runs, and monitors activities in alignment with the direction set by the governance body to achieve enterprise objectives. Governance sets the \"what and why\"; management handles the \"how.\" On the exam, if a stem asks who is <em>ultimately accountable</em> for IT governance, the answer is the board; if it asks who executes strategy day to day, that is executive/IT management. Confusing the two is a frequent trap.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Dimension</th><th>Governance (board)</th><th>Management (executives)</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Purpose</td><td>Set direction, oversee, hold accountable</td><td>Plan, build, run, monitor</td></tr><tr><td>COBIT domain</td><td>EDM — Evaluate, Direct, Monitor</td><td>APO, BAI, DSS, MEA</td></tr><tr><td>Time horizon</td><td>Strategic, long-term</td><td>Tactical and operational</td></tr><tr><td>Key artifacts</td><td>Charter, risk appetite, strategy approval</td><td>Plans, budgets, projects, operations</td></tr><tr><td>Auditor checks</td><td>Is oversight defined and exercised?</td><td>Do processes execute the direction?</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Frameworks: COBIT 2019 and ISO/IEC 38500</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>COBIT 2019</span> is ISACA's framework for the governance and management of enterprise IT. It organizes 40 governance and management objectives across five domains — one governance domain, EDM; and four management domains: Align/Plan/Organize (APO), Build/Acquire/Implement (BAI), Deliver/Service/Support (DSS), and Monitor/Evaluate/Assess (MEA). It introduces <span class='keyterm'>design factors</span> that tailor the governance system to the enterprise's context (enterprise strategy, risk profile, threat landscape, size, sourcing model), and it separates governance from management explicitly. <span class='keyterm'>ISO/IEC 38500</span> is the international standard for corporate governance of IT, built on six principles — responsibility, strategy, acquisition, performance, conformance, and human behavior — and the same Evaluate-Direct-Monitor cycle for directors. The auditor uses these frameworks as criteria: they define what \"good\" governance looks like, and the auditor compares the enterprise's actual structures against them to identify gaps. The auditor does not impose a framework; it evaluates against the criteria management has adopted, or notes the absence of any recognized framework as a weakness.</p><p>COBIT 2019 is also built on <span class='keyterm'>governance principles</span> worth recognizing: the governance system should meet stakeholder needs, be built from components (processes, structures, information flows, culture, skills), be a holistic rather than piecemeal effort, be dynamically tailored via design factors, and — most importantly for this domain — maintain a clear <span class='keyterm'>distinction between governance and management</span>. The auditor uses these to test whether the enterprise's approach is coherent or a collection of disconnected practices. Value creation in COBIT is framed as balancing benefits realization against risk optimization and resource optimization — the three governance objectives the board must keep in equilibrium. When an exam item asks what IT governance ultimately exists to deliver, the answer is value to stakeholders through that balance, not technology for its own sake.</p><h3>The IT Organization and Reporting Lines</h3><p>Structure is itself a control. The auditor examines the IT organization chart for appropriate <span class='keyterm'>segregation of duties</span> — for example, that development, operations, and security are separated so no single individual can both write and deploy code to production unchecked. Where the organization is too small to fully segregate, the auditor evaluates whether <span class='keyterm'>compensating controls</span> (supervisory review, logging, independent reconciliation) fill the gap. Reporting lines carry governance weight: a chief information security officer who reports to the CIO may face pressure to soften findings that reflect poorly on IT delivery, so many organizations give security an independent line to risk or the board. The auditor does not prescribe one structure, but assesses whether the chosen structure preserves the independence and oversight that governance requires. Steering-committee minutes are prime evidence here — they reveal whether investment decisions are genuinely challenged and prioritized against the business case, or merely ratified.</p><p>Finally, the auditor evaluates whether governance produces <span class='keyterm'>accountability</span>. Roles such as the CIO, business process owners, data owners, and the risk function should have documented responsibilities, and a responsibility-assignment convention (for example RACI — responsible, accountable, consulted, informed) helps confirm that for each key activity someone is unambiguously accountable. Diffuse accountability is a governance failure: when \"everyone\" owns security or data quality, no one does. The auditor tests whether decision rights are defined — who may approve an IT investment above a threshold, who may accept a risk, who may authorize an exception — because undefined decision rights lead either to paralysis or to unauthorized commitments. Read together, structure, framework, strategy, and accountability let the auditor form a defensible opinion on whether IT is genuinely governed in the interest of the enterprise, or simply managed by IT for IT.</p><h3>Structures: Board, Steering Committee, and Roles</h3><p>The auditor evaluates whether governance structures exist with clear mandates. The <span class='keyterm'>board</span> approves IT strategy, sets risk appetite, and monitors value and risk. An <span class='keyterm'>IT strategy committee</span> operates at board level to advise on strategic direction and major investment. The <span class='keyterm'>IT steering committee</span> operates at executive level: composed of senior business and IT leaders, it prioritizes and approves major IT investments, allocates resources, and monitors project and service performance against the business case. A recurring exam point: the steering committee's role is <em>prioritization and oversight of IT initiatives aligned to business needs</em>, not technical design. The auditor verifies the committee has a charter (terms of reference), appropriate membership (business, not only IT), regular meetings, and documented decisions. Separation of duties at the top also matters — the auditor watches for a CIO who both sets strategy and independently assures its execution, or a lack of independent oversight of IT spending. Reporting lines are relevant too: an internal audit function that reports to the CIO it audits has an independence problem the auditor should flag.</p><h3>IT Strategy and Business Alignment</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Strategic alignment</span> means the IT strategy is derived from and supports the business strategy, and that IT plans (tactical and operational) cascade from it. The auditor evaluates whether a documented IT strategic plan exists, whether it traces to business objectives, whether it is approved by the appropriate governance body, and whether it is refreshed as the business changes. A strategy that IT wrote in isolation, or one that is years stale, is a governance weakness regardless of how technically sound it looks. The <span class='keyterm'>IT balanced scorecard (BSC)</span> is a favored tool for translating strategy into measurable objectives across perspectives — commonly a corporate-contribution (or financial) perspective, a user/customer perspective, an operational-excellence (internal-process) perspective, and a future-orientation (learning-and-growth/innovation) perspective. It links IT performance metrics back to strategy, so the auditor can assess whether IT is measuring what matters to the business rather than only technical uptime. The auditor confirms the scorecard's measures are defined, owned, populated with real data, and reviewed by management.</p><p>Alignment is not a one-time event but a maintained relationship, and the auditor tests the mechanisms that sustain it. Does IT participate in business planning early enough to shape feasible commitments, or is it handed objectives it cannot meet? Is there a portfolio view that ties each significant IT investment back to a business objective, so the board can see what its money is buying? A useful concept is the <span class='keyterm'>enterprise goals to IT goals cascade</span> in COBIT, which traces stakeholder drivers down to enterprise goals, then to alignment (IT) goals, and finally to governance and management objectives — giving the auditor a documented chain to test whether IT activity actually serves stated business intent. Where the chain breaks — an IT initiative that maps to no business goal, or a business goal with no IT support — the auditor has a concrete alignment finding rather than a vague impression. The overarching audit judgment for this section is whether governance is exercised — direction set, decisions documented, performance monitored — or whether the structures are nominal, meeting rarely and rubber-stamping whatever IT proposes.</p><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div><p>Memorize <b>governance = board = EDM (Evaluate, Direct, Monitor)</b> and <b>management = APO/BAI/DSS/MEA</b>. If asked who is <b>ultimately accountable</b> for IT governance, it is the <b>board of directors</b>. The <b>IT steering committee</b> prioritizes and oversees IT investments aligned to the business — it does not perform technical design. Alignment of IT strategy to business strategy is the recurring \"best answer\" theme.</p></div><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div><p>An auditor finds IT has an ambitious three-year technology roadmap authored entirely within IT, with no evidence it was reviewed against the corporate strategy or approved by any board-level or steering body. The finding is a <b>lack of strategic alignment and governance oversight</b>: however good the roadmap, IT investment direction is being set without business validation, so IT may deliver capability the business did not ask for and will not fund.</p></div>"},
{"heading":"IT Policies, Standards, Procedures, and Practices","body":"<p>Policies are the instrument through which governance direction becomes operational rules. The auditor evaluates whether the enterprise maintains a coherent <span class='keyterm'>policy framework</span> that flows from top-level intent down to executable steps, is approved at the right level, is communicated, is enforced, and is kept current. A well-formed hierarchy is one of the clearest indicators that governance is real and not decorative.</p><h3>The Document Hierarchy</h3><p>The exam expects precise command of the hierarchy and the differences among its levels. A <span class='keyterm'>policy</span> is a high-level statement of management intent and direction — mandatory, broad, and relatively stable (for example, \"information assets shall be classified and protected according to their sensitivity\"). It is approved by senior management or the board and answers <em>why</em> and <em>what</em> at a principle level. A <span class='keyterm'>standard</span> is a mandatory rule that specifies uniform use of a technology, method, or configuration to support a policy (for example, \"all portable devices shall use AES-256 full-disk encryption\"). Standards make policies enforceable and testable. A <span class='keyterm'>procedure</span> is a detailed, step-by-step description of how to perform a task to comply with a policy or standard (for example, the exact steps to provision a new user account). Procedures are mandatory and operational. A <span class='keyterm'>guideline</span> is a recommended, non-mandatory practice offering discretion where a rigid rule is unnecessary. A <span class='keyterm'>baseline</span> is a minimum mandatory configuration or level of security for a category of systems, establishing a consistent floor.</p><p>The relationships among these documents are as important as the definitions. Policies are few, high-level, and change rarely; as one descends the hierarchy, documents become more numerous, more specific, and more frequently updated, because they reference particular technologies and steps that evolve. A single access-control policy might spawn several standards (password strength, multifactor, privileged access), each standard several procedures, and the whole set a baseline defining the default hardened configuration. The exam frequently probes whether the candidate can place a given statement at the correct level: \"employees must protect confidential information\" is policy-level intent; \"passwords must be at least 14 characters\" is a standard; \"to reset a password, verify identity via the following three steps\" is a procedure; \"consider using a passphrase\" is a guideline. Mislabeling a mandatory standard as a discretionary guideline, or vice versa, changes whether non-compliance is a violation or merely a missed suggestion — a distinction with real control consequences.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Level</th><th>Mandatory?</th><th>Nature</th><th>Approved by</th><th>Example</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Policy</td><td>Yes</td><td>High-level intent (why/what)</td><td>Board / senior management</td><td>\"Assets shall be classified and protected.\"</td></tr><tr><td>Standard</td><td>Yes</td><td>Specific mandatory rule</td><td>Senior/IT management</td><td>\"Use AES-256 disk encryption.\"</td></tr><tr><td>Baseline</td><td>Yes</td><td>Minimum required config</td><td>IT management</td><td>\"Servers hardened to CIS Level 1.\"</td></tr><tr><td>Procedure</td><td>Yes</td><td>Step-by-step how-to</td><td>Process owner</td><td>\"Steps to onboard a user.\"</td></tr><tr><td>Guideline</td><td>No</td><td>Recommended practice</td><td>Process owner</td><td>\"Suggested password-manager use.\"</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>What the Auditor Evaluates</h3><p>The auditor assesses the policy framework across several attributes. <span class='keyterm'>Existence and coverage:</span> do policies exist for the domains that matter (information security, acceptable use, access, change, data classification, privacy, third parties, business continuity)? <span class='keyterm'>Approval and authority:</span> was each document approved at an appropriate level, giving it force? A security \"policy\" a technician wrote and no executive endorsed carries no authority. <span class='keyterm'>Communication:</span> are policies distributed and acknowledged so staff know their obligations? Unread policies do not control behavior. <span class='keyterm'>Enforcement:</span> are there consequences for violations, and are they applied consistently? <span class='keyterm'>Currency and review:</span> is each document reviewed on a defined cycle (commonly annually or on significant change) with evidence of that review? A policy referencing retired technology or defunct roles signals a maintenance failure.</p><p>Alignment is equally important. Standards must trace to a policy, procedures to a standard or policy. When the auditor finds a procedure with no governing policy, or a policy with no standards or procedures to operationalize it, the framework is broken: intent without execution, or execution without mandate. The auditor also checks that policies are consistent with each other and with external obligations — a data-retention policy contradicting a legal-hold requirement is a control conflict. Version control matters as well: the auditor confirms staff are working from the current, approved version, not a stale copy on a shared drive.</p><h3>The Policy Lifecycle</h3><p>Policies have a lifecycle the auditor can test end to end. Development gathers requirements from law, risk, and business need; drafting produces the document with a named owner; review circulates it to stakeholders (legal, security, affected business units); approval by an authority with the standing to mandate it gives it force; publication and communication reach the people it binds, ideally with acknowledgment; enforcement applies it, with consequences for breach; and periodic review — on a defined cycle or triggered by significant change (a new system, a merger, a new regulation) — keeps it current before the document is eventually retired. The auditor looks for evidence at each stage: an approval signature and date, a distribution and acknowledgment record, a review log. A common weakness is a robust creation process with no maintenance process, so the library ages into irrelevance. Another is an <span class='keyterm'>exception process</span> that is missing or uncontrolled — mature frameworks let business units request documented, time-bound, risk-assessed exceptions to a standard, and the auditor checks that exceptions are approved by an appropriate authority, tracked, and revisited rather than granted informally and forgotten.</p><h3>Practices and the Reality Gap</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Practices</span> are what people actually do. The most consequential audit work here is comparing documented policy to observed practice. A pristine policy binder means little if staff bypass it. The auditor gathers evidence — configuration samples, tickets, interviews, observation — to determine whether behavior conforms. A common finding is a strong policy set that operations ignore because it is impractical, unenforced, or unknown; the recommendation is to reconcile the two, either by enforcing the policy or by revising it to a workable, still-adequate control. The auditor does not simply accept the documented control as operating; the exam repeatedly rewards testing the practice, not trusting the paper. Where policy and practice diverge, the auditor determines which is the risk — usually the gap itself — and reports it with the root cause (impracticality, poor communication, or absent enforcement) so management can remediate the cause rather than the symptom.</p><p>The auditor also weighs whether the framework as a whole is <span class='keyterm'>fit for the organization</span>. Over-engineered policy libraries that no one can navigate are as ineffective as absent ones; if staff cannot readily find the rule that governs a task, they will improvise. A single sprawling document that mixes principle, rule, and step-by-step instruction is hard to maintain and hard to follow, which is why the hierarchy exists. The auditor evaluates whether the library is proportionate to the organization's size and risk, logically organized, and accessible. Cross-references and a defined ownership model — each document assigned to a role, not a person who may leave — indicate a maintainable framework. Where policies simply restate law verbatim without translating it into the organization's own testable rules, the auditor notes that compliance intent has not been operationalized. The strongest evidence that a policy framework is real is a clean trace from an external requirement or business risk, down through policy and standard, to a procedure a named owner performs and the auditor can observe in action.</p><p>One more test the auditor applies is <span class='keyterm'>consistency of enforcement</span>. A rule enforced against junior staff but waived for executives is not a control; it is theater, and it undermines the credibility of the whole framework. The auditor samples across roles and business units to see whether the same standard is applied uniformly, and whether disciplinary or corrective action actually follows documented violations. Selective enforcement, undocumented informal exceptions, and \"temporary\" waivers that never expire are recurring findings that the exam expects the auditor to treat as control weaknesses rather than acceptable pragmatism. The recurring lesson across this section is that documents govern behavior only when they are authoritative, known, followed, and maintained; the auditor's job is to test each of those conditions with evidence, not to admire a well-formatted binder. A policy no one can produce on request, cannot show was approved, cannot show was communicated, or cannot show is enforced, provides no assurance no matter how comprehensive its contents appear, and the auditor's report should say so plainly rather than credit the document for good intentions.</p><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div><p>Know the hierarchy cold: <b>policy</b> (high-level intent, mandatory) → <b>standard</b> (specific mandatory rule) → <b>procedure</b> (step-by-step, mandatory) → <b>guideline</b> (recommended, optional). A <b>baseline</b> is a minimum mandatory configuration. If a stem describes a \"recommended\" practice with discretion, it is a <b>guideline</b>. A policy has authority only if approved at the appropriate senior level.</p></div><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div><p>During fieldwork the auditor finds a comprehensive information-security policy approved by the board, but interviews reveal most staff have never read it and several documented controls are routinely bypassed for convenience. The finding centers on the <b>gap between documented policy and actual practice</b>: the policy is not communicated or enforced, so it provides paper assurance only. The auditor tests practice, reports the gap, and recommends communication, acknowledgment, and enforcement — not merely rewriting the document.</p></div>"},
{"heading":"Enterprise Architecture and Considerations","body":"<p><span class='keyterm'>Enterprise architecture (EA)</span> is the discipline that describes the structure of the enterprise — its business processes, information, applications, and technology — and how they fit together to support strategy. It is the blueprint that keeps IT investments coherent instead of a sprawl of point solutions that do not interoperate. The auditor evaluates whether an EA function exists, whether it is governed, and whether it actually influences how the organization acquires and builds IT, because EA is a primary control against duplication, incompatibility, and technical debt.</p><h3>Why EA Matters to the Auditor</h3><p>From an assurance perspective, EA is a governance mechanism. It provides a documented <span class='keyterm'>current state</span> (the \"as-is\" baseline of processes, data, applications, and infrastructure) and a <span class='keyterm'>target state</span> (the \"to-be\" design that supports strategic objectives). The difference between them is the <span class='keyterm'>gap</span>, and the roadmap of projects that closes the gap is the <span class='keyterm'>transition plan</span>. The auditor evaluates whether these artifacts exist and are current, because without a documented target state, individual projects have no shared destination and tend to optimize locally while degrading the whole. An enterprise that cannot produce an inventory of its applications and their interdependencies has an EA weakness that raises operational, security, and continuity risk.</p><p>EA typically decomposes into layers or domains, and the auditor benefits from recognizing them because findings often trace to a specific layer. The <span class='keyterm'>business architecture</span> describes processes, capabilities, and organizational units — the demand side that IT exists to serve. The <span class='keyterm'>data (information) architecture</span> defines the enterprise's data entities, their authoritative sources, and how they flow, which is the foundation for data governance and quality. The <span class='keyterm'>application architecture</span> maps the applications and the interfaces among them. The <span class='keyterm'>technology (infrastructure) architecture</span> covers the platforms, networks, and hardware that run everything. A coherent EA keeps these layers aligned so that, for example, every critical business capability is supported by an identified application running on a supported platform, with data sourced from a defined system of record. Misalignment across layers — a business capability with no owning system, or two applications claiming to be the authoritative customer record — is precisely what EA is meant to surface and prevent.</p><table><thead><tr><th>EA layer</th><th>Describes</th><th>Example content</th><th>Auditor's concern</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Business</td><td>Processes, functions, org units</td><td>Order-to-cash process, capabilities</td><td>Do systems support real business capabilities?</td></tr><tr><td>Data/Information</td><td>Data entities and flows</td><td>Customer master, data lineage</td><td>Is authoritative data defined and consistent?</td></tr><tr><td>Application</td><td>Applications and interfaces</td><td>ERP, CRM, integration map</td><td>Duplication, unsupported apps, interface risk</td></tr><tr><td>Technology</td><td>Infrastructure and platforms</td><td>Servers, networks, middleware</td><td>Standardization, obsolescence, resilience</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>TOGAF and Architecture Frameworks</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>TOGAF (The Open Group Architecture Framework)</span> is the most widely referenced EA framework. Its core is the <span class='keyterm'>Architecture Development Method (ADM)</span>, an iterative cycle of phases — architecture vision, then the business, data, application, and technology architectures, then opportunities and solutions, migration planning, implementation governance, and change management, all revolving around requirements management. TOGAF also defines an <span class='keyterm'>architecture repository</span> and content framework. Other frameworks the auditor may encounter include the <span class='keyterm'>Zachman Framework</span> (a taxonomy classifying architecture artifacts by perspective and interrogative — what, how, where, who, when, why) and, in government, FEAF. The auditor does not need to design architecture, but should recognize that these frameworks provide criteria: a mature EA follows a defined method, maintains a repository, and governs conformance of projects to the target architecture.</p><h3>EA Governance</h3><p>The most audit-relevant concept is <span class='keyterm'>EA governance</span> — the process that ensures projects conform to the approved architecture and that deviations are consciously approved rather than accidental. Typically an <span class='keyterm'>architecture review board (ARB)</span> reviews significant initiatives for alignment with standards and the target state, and grants or denies <span class='keyterm'>architecture exceptions/waivers</span> when a deviation is justified. The auditor evaluates whether such a body exists, whether projects are actually routed through it, whether exceptions are documented with rationale and expiry, and whether accumulated exceptions are periodically revisited (an exception left permanent becomes uncontrolled drift). Without enforcement, an EA is merely aspirational documentation, and the exam treats \"architecture exists on paper but is not enforced on projects\" as a genuine weakness.</p><p>EA governance also connects to the investment and change processes. The auditor evaluates whether architectural conformance is a gate in the project lifecycle — reviewed at concept and design, not discovered at go-live — and whether the portfolio and steering committee consider architectural fit when approving spend. An organization that funds solutions purely on business-case return, ignoring whether they align with the target architecture, will accumulate fragmentation even with disciplined project management. The auditor further assesses the maturity and currency of EA artifacts: a target-state model drawn three years ago and never revisited may itself be obsolete, so conformance to it could institutionalize outdated choices. Living EA is refreshed as strategy and technology shift. Where a formal EA function does not exist, the auditor does not necessarily conclude the organization is failing — small enterprises may govern architecture informally — but it does assess whether <em>some</em> mechanism prevents uncontrolled proliferation, and reports the risk if none does.</p><h3>Key Architecture Considerations</h3><p>Several qualities recur when the auditor assesses whether the architecture supports business needs and controls risk. <span class='keyterm'>Interoperability and standardization</span> reduce integration cost and single points of failure; a proliferation of one-off, undocumented interfaces is a red flag. <span class='keyterm'>Scalability and capacity</span> ensure the architecture can grow with demand — an EA concern that links directly to capacity planning. <span class='keyterm'>Security by design</span> means controls are architected in (segmentation, identity, encryption placement) rather than retrofitted. <span class='keyterm'>Resilience</span> — redundancy, recoverability, absence of single points of failure — is an architectural property that underpins continuity. <span class='keyterm'>Obsolescence and technical debt</span>: the auditor looks for unsupported platforms and end-of-life components, which raise security and availability risk. Finally, EA should be a living input to portfolio decisions: proposed investments are evaluated against the target architecture so the organization stops funding solutions that increase fragmentation. The auditor's summary judgment is whether EA is an active governance control shaping IT decisions, or a shelf document disconnected from how work actually gets approved and built.</p><p>From a control perspective, EA supports several assurance objectives the auditor cares about directly. A current application and infrastructure inventory underpins <span class='keyterm'>business continuity and disaster recovery</span> planning, because you cannot recover what you have not catalogued or prioritized. It supports <span class='keyterm'>security</span>, because knowing where sensitive data lives and how systems connect is the precondition for protecting them and for scoping assessments. It supports <span class='keyterm'>change management</span>, because understanding interdependencies lets the organization predict the blast radius of a change. And it supports <span class='keyterm'>cost and value management</span>, because visibility into duplication and obsolescence lets the enterprise rationalize its estate. When the auditor evaluates any of these areas and finds the underlying architectural information missing or unreliable, the root cause frequently traces back to an immature EA. Thus the auditor treats EA not as an academic exercise but as a foundational governance control whose absence quietly weakens continuity, security, and cost discipline across the enterprise, and reports its state accordingly.</p><p>When assessing EA maturity, the auditor looks for a defined method (such as TOGAF's ADM or an equivalent), a maintained repository of current- and target-state artifacts, an active governance body that reviews conformance, a documented and enforced exception process, and a clear linkage from architecture into the investment and change processes. The absence of any one of these signals a gap: a repository with no governance body produces documentation no one heeds; a governance body with no repository has nothing to govern against; a method with no linkage to funding decisions cannot influence what actually gets built. A useful audit test is to trace a recently completed significant project backward — was it reviewed for architectural fit, were deviations documented and approved, did it update the repository on completion? If the answer is no, EA is not operating as a control regardless of how impressive the framework looks on paper. The auditor's conclusion, as always, rests on whether the architecture actually shapes decisions and constrains projects — the observable behavior — rather than on the existence of the artifacts alone. An enterprise architecture that is documented, governed, enforced, and connected to funding and change decisions is a powerful control against fragmentation and risk; one that exists only as diagrams no project consults is a cost with no corresponding benefit.</p><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div><p><b>TOGAF's ADM</b> is the method; the audit-relevant idea is <b>EA governance</b> — projects must conform to the approved target architecture, with documented, expiring <b>exceptions</b> for deviations. The <b>gap</b> between current and target state drives the <b>transition/migration plan</b>. \"Architecture documented but not enforced on projects\" is a real weakness, not an acceptable state.</p></div><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div><p>An auditor reviewing a new customer portal finds it introduced a third, incompatible customer database and several undocumented interfaces, bypassing the architecture review board entirely. The finding is a failure of <b>EA governance</b>: absent enforcement, the project increased data duplication and integration risk. The recommendation is to route significant initiatives through the ARB, evaluate them against the target-state architecture, and document any approved exceptions with an expiry and remediation plan.</p></div>"},
{"heading":"Enterprise Risk Management","body":"<p><span class='keyterm'>Enterprise risk management (ERM)</span> is the framework by which an organization identifies, assesses, treats, monitors, and reports risk across the enterprise so that risk-taking stays within the boundaries the board has set. IT risk is a component of enterprise risk, and the auditor evaluates whether IT risk is identified and managed within that enterprise framework rather than in an isolated technical silo. The exam leans heavily on precise risk vocabulary, so command of the terms is essential.</p><h3>Risk Appetite, Tolerance, and Capacity</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Risk appetite</span> is the amount and type of risk the organization is willing to pursue in pursuit of its objectives — a strategic, board-set boundary. <span class='keyterm'>Risk tolerance</span> is the acceptable variation around specific objectives or risks, the practical thresholds that operationalize appetite (for example, \"unplanned downtime of the order system must not exceed four hours per quarter\"). <span class='keyterm'>Risk capacity</span> is the maximum risk the organization could absorb before threatening its viability. The auditor evaluates whether appetite is defined and approved by the board, whether tolerances flow from it, and whether decisions and controls actually respect those boundaries. Controls calibrated far above appetite waste resources; controls below tolerance leave the organization exposed beyond what the board accepted. The auditor's role is not to set appetite — that is a board decision — but to evaluate whether appetite is defined, communicated, and used as the reference point for risk decisions, and whether the organization actually operates within it.</p><h3>Frameworks and the Enterprise View</h3><p>ERM is typically anchored in a recognized framework. <span class='keyterm'>COSO ERM</span> integrates risk with strategy and performance across five components — governance and culture; strategy and objective-setting; performance (identification, assessment, prioritization); review and revision; and information, communication, and reporting. <span class='keyterm'>ISO 31000</span> offers principles, a framework, and a process for risk management applicable to any organization. ISACA's own <span class='keyterm'>Risk IT</span> framework (now folded into COBIT) focuses specifically on IT risk as a category of business risk. The auditor uses whichever framework the enterprise has adopted as criteria, and — importantly — evaluates whether IT risk is integrated into enterprise risk rather than managed separately by the IT department in a technical vacuum. A telling weakness is an IT-only risk process whose outputs never reach the enterprise risk committee, so technology exposures that could threaten strategic objectives are invisible to the board that owns the appetite.</p><h3>Inherent, Residual, and the Risk Equation</h3><p>Risk is a function of the likelihood of a threat exploiting a vulnerability and the resulting business impact. <span class='keyterm'>Inherent risk</span> is the risk before any controls are applied — the natural exposure of the activity. <span class='keyterm'>Residual risk</span> is what remains after controls operate. The purpose of controls is to reduce inherent risk to a residual level within tolerance. A subtle but critical point: residual risk can never be fully eliminated, and it is residual risk — not inherent risk — that management must formally accept. The auditor evaluates whether residual risk is measured, compared to tolerance, and consciously accepted by an appropriately senior owner. Where residual risk exceeds tolerance and no action is planned, that is a reportable finding.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Treatment</th><th>What it means</th><th>Example</th><th>Auditor note</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Avoid (eliminate)</td><td>Stop the activity causing the risk</td><td>Discontinue a risky product line</td><td>Removes benefit too; used for intolerable risk</td></tr><tr><td>Mitigate (reduce)</td><td>Apply controls to lower likelihood/impact</td><td>Add access controls, backups</td><td>Most common; verify controls operate</td></tr><tr><td>Transfer (share)</td><td>Shift financial impact to a third party</td><td>Insurance, outsourcing with liability</td><td>Transfers loss, not accountability</td></tr><tr><td>Accept (retain)</td><td>Consciously bear the residual risk</td><td>Accept low-impact residual after controls</td><td>Must be by an owner with authority</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>The Risk Management Process and the Register</h3><p>The process is a cycle: establish context, identify risks, analyze (likelihood and impact), evaluate against criteria, treat (select from avoid/mitigate/transfer/accept), and monitor and review. The central artifact is the <span class='keyterm'>risk register</span> — a documented inventory of identified risks with their owners, assessed likelihood and impact, current controls, residual rating, chosen treatment, and status. The auditor evaluates whether a register exists, is comprehensive, is current, assigns ownership, and is reviewed by governance. A risk register that is never updated, or lists risks without owners or treatment decisions, indicates ERM is not operating. Note the important distinction between transferring risk and transferring accountability: buying insurance or outsourcing a process shifts financial loss, but the organization remains accountable to regulators and customers — a heavily tested point. The auditor also distinguishes qualitative assessment (high/medium/low ratings, useful when data is scarce) from quantitative assessment (monetary values such as single-loss and annualized-loss expectancy), and evaluates whether the method chosen suits the decision at hand.</p><h3>KRIs, KPIs, and Monitoring</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Key risk indicators (KRIs)</span> are metrics that provide early warning of rising risk exposure (for example, a climbing count of failed logins or overdue patches), whereas <span class='keyterm'>key performance indicators (KPIs)</span> measure achievement of objectives. The auditor evaluates whether KRIs are defined with thresholds that trigger action, are monitored, and are reported to those who can respond. KRIs that no one watches, or thresholds that never trigger escalation, are ineffective controls. The auditor also distinguishes KRIs (leading, predictive of exposure) from KPIs (lagging, measuring outcomes) and checks that the organization has enough of the former to see risk coming, not only the latter to record what already went wrong.</p><h3>Risk Reporting and Aggregation</h3><p>Risk information is only valuable if it reaches decision-makers in a form they can act on. The auditor evaluates the reporting chain: are risks aggregated to an enterprise view, escalated when they cross tolerance, and reported to the risk committee and board on a defined cadence? A frequent gap is that individual risks are tracked in departmental registers but never rolled up, so no one sees that many small correlated exposures sum to an intolerable concentration. The auditor also assesses whether reporting is honest — whether uncomfortable risks are surfaced or quietly downgraded, and whether the risk function has the independence to report what management would rather not hear. Timeliness matters too: a risk reported months after it emerged has already done its damage. The quality of the risk register and the discipline of escalation are the auditor's best evidence that ERM is a live process rather than an annual compliance ritual.</p><h3>The Three Lines Model</h3><p>The <span class='keyterm'>Three Lines Model</span> (IIA) clarifies accountability. The <span class='keyterm'>first line</span> — operational management — owns and manages risk in day-to-day activities. The <span class='keyterm'>second line</span> — risk and compliance functions — sets policy, provides oversight and expertise, and monitors the first line. The <span class='keyterm'>third line</span> — internal audit — provides independent, objective assurance to the board over the whole system, and it must remain independent of the first two lines to preserve objectivity. The auditor's own role sits in the third line; the exam expects you to recognize that internal audit does not own or manage risk (that would impair independence) but provides assurance that risk management is designed and operating. Where the model is blurred — for example, audit designing the controls it later assures — the auditor flags the independence conflict.</p><p>Bringing the pieces together, the auditor's evaluation of ERM asks a chain of questions: Has the board set and communicated a risk appetite? Does a documented process identify, assess, treat, and monitor risk consistently? Is there a maintained risk register with owners, ratings, and treatment decisions? Are residual risks compared to tolerance and formally accepted at the right level? Are KRIs monitored and risks escalated and reported to those who own the appetite? And is the whole arrangement independent enough — via the three lines — to be trusted? Where the answers are yes and the evidence supports them, the auditor can conclude risk is being managed within the boundaries the board accepted. Where they are no — an appetite no one defined, a register no one updates, residual risk no one accepted — the auditor reports that risk is effectively unmanaged, however much activity surrounds it. The exam consistently rewards this evidence-driven, boundary-referenced view of risk over answers that equate buying tools or writing policies with actually managing exposure. The auditor stays in the assurance seat throughout: it does not choose the treatment or own the risk, but reports independently on whether the risk-management system is designed well and operating as intended, so the board can rely on it when steering the enterprise within its chosen appetite.</p><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div><p><b>Residual risk</b> — not inherent risk — is what management formally <b>accepts</b>. Treatment options are <b>avoid, mitigate, transfer, accept</b>. Transferring risk (insurance/outsourcing) shifts financial loss but <b>never</b> transfers accountability. In the <b>Three Lines Model</b>, internal audit is the <b>third line</b> and must stay independent of the first (operations) and second (risk/compliance) lines.</p></div><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div><p>Management tells the auditor it has \"eliminated\" a data-loss risk by purchasing cyber-insurance. The auditor should recognize this as <b>risk transfer, not elimination</b>: the policy addresses financial loss but leaves the likelihood of an incident and the organization's regulatory and reputational accountability intact. The register should show the residual risk, the transfer treatment, and any remaining exposure explicitly accepted by an owner with authority.</p></div>"},
{"heading":"Privacy Program and Principles","body":"<p>A <span class='keyterm'>privacy program</span> is the governance structure through which an organization manages personal data in accordance with law, contractual obligations, and stakeholder expectations. Privacy is distinct from security: security protects the confidentiality, integrity, and availability of information generally, while privacy governs the appropriate collection, use, disclosure, retention, and disposal of <span class='keyterm'>personal data</span> — information relating to an identified or identifiable individual. Strong security is necessary but not sufficient for privacy; an organization can secure data perfectly and still violate privacy by using it for undisclosed purposes. The auditor evaluates whether a privacy program exists, is governed, and operates.</p><h3>Core Privacy Principles</h3><p>Widely recognized privacy principles — drawn from the OECD guidelines, GDPR, and generally accepted privacy frameworks — give the auditor criteria against which to assess the program. <span class='keyterm'>Lawfulness, fairness, and transparency:</span> processing must have a lawful basis and be disclosed to individuals. <span class='keyterm'>Purpose limitation:</span> data is collected for specified purposes and not repurposed incompatibly. <span class='keyterm'>Data minimization:</span> collect only what is necessary. <span class='keyterm'>Accuracy:</span> keep data correct and up to date. <span class='keyterm'>Storage limitation:</span> retain no longer than necessary. <span class='keyterm'>Integrity and confidentiality:</span> protect data with appropriate security. <span class='keyterm'>Accountability:</span> the organization is responsible for and can demonstrate compliance. The auditor evaluates whether program controls give effect to each principle — for instance, whether retention schedules enforce storage limitation, or whether collection forms honor minimization.</p><h3>Governance of the Privacy Program</h3><p>Beyond principles, the auditor evaluates the program's governance scaffolding. Is there a designated owner — a privacy officer, a chief privacy officer, or, where the law requires it, a <span class='keyterm'>Data Protection Officer (DPO)</span> — with defined authority, adequate resources, and enough independence to challenge business practices that create privacy risk? Is there a board-approved privacy policy and a set of supporting standards and procedures, mirroring the document hierarchy of Section 3? Does the program maintain a <span class='keyterm'>data inventory (record of processing activities)</span> that identifies what personal data is held, where it lives, why it is processed, its lawful basis, who it is shared with, and how long it is kept? This inventory is the backbone of a functioning privacy program, because almost every downstream obligation — fulfilling data-subject rights, honoring retention limits, reporting breaches, assessing new processing — depends on knowing where personal data is. An organization that cannot produce this inventory cannot credibly claim its privacy obligations are under control, and the auditor treats its absence as a fundamental weakness.</p><h3>Privacy by Design and by Default</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Privacy by design</span> means embedding privacy protections into systems and processes from the outset rather than bolting them on later; <span class='keyterm'>privacy by default</span> means the most privacy-protective settings apply unless the individual chooses otherwise. These are explicit GDPR obligations and are a favored exam theme because they mirror the audit preference for controls designed in, not retrofitted. The auditor evaluates whether privacy requirements enter the system development lifecycle early — captured in requirements, reviewed at design, and validated before launch — rather than being discovered in production. Retrofitting privacy after a system is live is expensive and often only partially effective, which is why the design-in approach is both the regulatory expectation and the audit-preferred control. Techniques that support these principles include pseudonymization and anonymization, data minimization at collection, granular access controls, and default settings that limit sharing — and the auditor checks that such techniques are actually applied where the risk warrants, not merely mentioned in policy.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Concept</th><th>Meaning</th><th>What the auditor checks</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Data subject</td><td>Individual the data is about</td><td>Are their rights supported operationally?</td></tr><tr><td>Controller</td><td>Determines purposes and means of processing</td><td>Accountability and lawful-basis records</td></tr><tr><td>Processor</td><td>Processes on the controller's behalf</td><td>Binding contract, instructions, limits</td></tr><tr><td>Consent</td><td>Freely given, specific, informed agreement</td><td>Opt-in, revocable, logged, granular</td></tr><tr><td>PIA / DPIA</td><td>Assessment of privacy risk of an activity</td><td>Performed for high-risk processing, acted on</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Data Subject Rights and Consent</h3><p>Modern privacy law grants individuals <span class='keyterm'>data subject rights</span>: to be informed, to access their data, to rectification, to erasure (the \"right to be forgotten\" under GDPR), to restrict or object to processing, and to data portability. The auditor evaluates whether the organization can actually fulfill these rights within legal timeframes — for example, whether it can locate and delete an individual's data across all systems, which tests the maturity of the data inventory. <span class='keyterm'>Consent</span>, where it is the lawful basis, must be freely given, specific, informed, and unambiguous, and it must be as easy to withdraw as to give. The auditor checks that consent is not bundled or pre-ticked, that it is logged, and that withdrawal propagates to downstream processing. A common finding is that consent is captured at collection but withdrawal is not honored across integrated systems. The auditor also notes that consent is only one of several lawful bases (others include contract, legal obligation, legitimate interests, and more); an organization that relies on consent where another basis would be more appropriate, or that treats consent as a formality rather than a genuine choice, has a design weakness the auditor should flag.</p><h3>Privacy Impact Assessments and Governance</h3><p>A <span class='keyterm'>Privacy Impact Assessment (PIA)</span> — called a <span class='keyterm'>Data Protection Impact Assessment (DPIA)</span> under GDPR — is a structured evaluation of the privacy risks of a new system, process, or data use, and of the controls that will address them. GDPR requires a DPIA for high-risk processing (large-scale sensitive data, systematic monitoring). The auditor evaluates whether PIAs/DPIAs are triggered by defined criteria, performed before launch, documented, and — crucially — whether their recommendations are implemented rather than filed and forgotten. The auditor also assesses governance: whether a designated privacy officer or, where required, a <span class='keyterm'>Data Protection Officer (DPO)</span> exists with appropriate independence and authority, whether a breach-response process meets notification obligations (such as GDPR's 72-hour rule), and whether privacy roles and training reach the staff who handle personal data. Cross-border transfers deserve attention too: the auditor checks whether transfers of personal data to other jurisdictions rely on a valid mechanism and respect data-residency requirements.</p><p>Third parties are a major privacy concern, because sharing personal data with processors and other partners extends the organization's exposure without extending its direct control. The auditor evaluates whether processor relationships are governed by binding contracts that limit processing to documented instructions, impose security and confidentiality obligations, restrict onward transfers and sub-processing, and grant audit or assurance rights. A controller remains accountable for personal data even when a processor handles it, so weak processor oversight is the controller's finding, not merely the vendor's. This links privacy directly to vendor management: due diligence, contractual safeguards, and ongoing monitoring of processors are privacy controls as much as procurement controls. Breach handling deserves the same scrutiny — the auditor checks that the incident process can detect a personal-data breach, assess its severity, notify the supervisory authority and affected individuals within required timeframes, and log the event, because notification obligations carry hard deadlines and significant penalties for failure.</p><p>Finally, the auditor assesses the human and monitoring dimensions. Are staff who handle personal data trained on their obligations, and is that training tracked? Does the organization monitor its own privacy compliance — through assessments, metrics, and periodic review — rather than assuming that a policy written once continues to be followed? Is privacy risk represented in the enterprise risk process, so that a serious privacy exposure reaches the board? The auditor's overall judgment is whether privacy is a governed, evidenced program — with owner, inventory, assessments, third-party controls, breach readiness, training, and rights fulfillment — or a policy statement without operating controls. As with every section of this domain, the exam rewards the conclusion grounded in evidence that controls actually operate over the answer that accepts management's assurance that personal data is \"handled appropriately.\" A privacy program is only as strong as its weakest operating link — a perfect policy undermined by an incomplete data map, an unfulfilled erasure request, or a processor no one oversees — and the auditor's value lies in finding that weak link before a regulator or a breach does, and in reporting it with enough specificity that management can close it. Privacy, in the end, is a governance outcome: it depends on the same disciplines — ownership, documented rules, inventory, assessment, monitoring, and independent assurance — that run through every other section of this domain.</p><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div><p>Distinguish <b>privacy</b> (appropriate use of personal data) from <b>security</b> (protecting CIA of data generally) — good security does not guarantee privacy. <b>Privacy by design</b> means building protections in from the start. A <b>DPIA/PIA</b> is required for high-risk processing and its recommendations must be acted on. <b>Consent</b> must be freely given, specific, informed, and as easy to withdraw as to give.</p></div><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div><p>An auditor finds the company collects consent at sign-up but cannot demonstrate that a customer's later withdrawal of consent stopped downstream marketing systems from processing their data. The finding is that <b>consent withdrawal does not propagate</b>, breaching purpose limitation and the requirement that withdrawal be effective. The root cause is often an incomplete data inventory, so the auditor's recommendation addresses both the propagation control and the underlying mapping of where personal data flows.</p></div>"},
{"heading":"Data Governance and Classification","body":"<p><span class='keyterm'>Data governance</span> is the exercise of authority and control over the management of data as an enterprise asset. Where privacy governs personal data specifically, data governance governs all data — its ownership, quality, classification, lifecycle, and use — so that the organization can trust the information it relies on to make decisions and to satisfy obligations. The auditor evaluates whether data is governed deliberately, with defined roles and controls, or whether it accumulates unmanaged across systems until no one can say what is authoritative, who owns it, or how sensitive it is. Poor data governance quietly undermines nearly everything else: reporting is unreliable, security cannot be scoped, retention cannot be enforced, and privacy rights cannot be fulfilled.</p><h3>Data Roles: Owner, Custodian, and Steward</h3><p>The exam is precise about data roles, and confusing them is a common error. The <span class='keyterm'>data owner</span> is a senior business person accountable for a data asset: they classify it, define who may access it and for what purpose, approve access requests, and are ultimately answerable for its protection and appropriate use. Ownership is a business accountability, not an IT function. The <span class='keyterm'>data custodian</span> — typically in IT — implements and operates the controls the owner specifies: storage, backup, encryption, access provisioning, and technical safeguards. The custodian executes; it does not decide classification or access policy. The <span class='keyterm'>data steward</span> is responsible for the day-to-day management of data quality, definitions, and standards on the owner's behalf, ensuring the data is accurate, consistent, and used according to agreed rules. The auditor tests whether these roles are assigned and understood: a frequent finding is that IT is treated as the de facto owner because no business owner was named, which means access and classification decisions are being made by people without the business context or authority to make them.</p><p>Underlying these roles is the broader governance structure. Mature organizations establish a <span class='keyterm'>data governance body</span> — a council or committee that sets data policies, resolves cross-functional data issues, and holds owners accountable — because data crosses departmental boundaries and needs an authority above any single business unit. The auditor evaluates whether such governance exists, whether data policies and standards are defined and approved (mirroring the policy hierarchy of Section 3), and whether the roles are backed by real authority rather than nominal titles. Without a governing body, data disputes (whose definition of \"active customer\" is correct, who may approve a new data feed) are resolved inconsistently or not at all, and the organization ends up with conflicting data that erodes trust in every report built on it.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Role</th><th>Typically who</th><th>Responsibility</th><th>What the auditor verifies</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Data owner</td><td>Senior business manager</td><td>Classify, authorize access, accountable for protection</td><td>Named owner exists and approves access</td></tr><tr><td>Data custodian</td><td>IT / operations</td><td>Implement and run controls the owner specifies</td><td>Controls match owner's requirements</td></tr><tr><td>Data steward</td><td>Business/data specialist</td><td>Data quality, definitions, standards</td><td>Quality is measured and managed</td></tr><tr><td>User</td><td>Any authorized person</td><td>Use data per policy and least privilege</td><td>Access matches role and need</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Classification Schemes</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Data classification</span> is the process of assigning data a sensitivity level so that protection can be proportionate to value and risk. A classification scheme defines a small number of levels — for example public, internal, confidential, and restricted (or a government-style scheme of unclassified, confidential, secret, top secret) — each with handling rules covering storage, transmission, access, retention, and disposal. Classification is the linchpin control because it determines how much protection data receives: over-classifying wastes resources and impedes work, while under-classifying leaves sensitive data exposed. The auditor evaluates whether a scheme exists, whether the levels are clearly defined with associated handling requirements, whether data owners have actually classified their data, and whether the classification drives real control differences rather than sitting as an unused label. A scheme that exists on paper but is not applied — data with no classification, or everything defaulted to the lowest level — provides no protection benefit. The auditor also checks that classification is reviewed as data changes sensitivity over time (information may become less sensitive with age, or more sensitive when aggregated). A subtle but tested point is <span class='keyterm'>aggregation risk</span>: individually innocuous data elements can become sensitive in combination — a list of names is low-risk, but the same names joined to salaries, health conditions, or locations may be highly sensitive — so classification must consider data in context, not just field by field. The auditor also verifies that classification labels actually travel with the data and drive downstream handling (encryption, access restrictions, disposal rules); a label that no control consumes is decoration.</p><h3>Data Quality and the Data Lifecycle</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Data quality</span> is the fitness of data for its purpose, assessed across dimensions such as accuracy, completeness, consistency, timeliness, validity, and uniqueness. Because decisions and controls depend on data, poor quality is a business risk in its own right — a duplicate customer record, a stale price, an incomplete address all cause downstream failures. The auditor evaluates whether data quality is defined, measured against those dimensions, monitored, and remediated, and whether ownership of quality is assigned (the steward's remit). The <span class='keyterm'>data lifecycle</span> — commonly framed as create/capture, store, use, share, archive, and destroy — is the frame the auditor uses to check that controls apply at every stage: is data validated at capture, protected in storage, controlled when shared, retained per schedule while needed, and securely disposed of when no longer required? <span class='keyterm'>Retention and disposal</span> deserve particular attention, because keeping data past its useful life increases cost, breach exposure, and privacy risk, while disposing of data still under legal hold is a serious failure. The auditor confirms retention schedules exist, reflect legal and business requirements, and are actually enforced, and that secure disposal (not just deletion) applies to sensitive data at end of life.</p><p>Underpinning all of this is the concept of a <span class='keyterm'>system of record</span> or authoritative source: for each important data element, the organization should designate which system holds the definitive version, so that reconciliation and reporting have a single trusted origin. Where multiple systems each claim authority for the same data with no reconciliation, the auditor has found a governance gap that produces conflicting reports and erodes trust in the numbers. Master data management and clear data definitions are the disciplines that address this. The auditor's overall judgment is whether data is treated as a governed enterprise asset — owned, classified, quality-managed, and lifecycle-controlled — or as an unmanaged byproduct of running systems. Because data governance underpins security, privacy, compliance reporting, and analytics alike, its weaknesses tend to surface as findings in many other areas, and the auditor traces them back to their common root here.</p><p>The auditor's tests in this area are concrete. To assess ownership, request the list of critical data assets and their named owners, then confirm those owners actually approve access. To assess classification, sample data stores and check whether they carry a classification and whether protection matches it. To assess quality, review whether quality dimensions are measured and whether known issues are tracked and remediated. To assess the lifecycle, trace a data element from capture (is it validated?) through retention (is a schedule enforced?) to disposal (is it securely destroyed, with evidence?). Where these tests fail — assets with no owner, unclassified sensitive data, unmeasured quality, retention that never purges — the auditor reports a data-governance deficiency and, because so much depends on it, flags the downstream risks to reporting reliability, security scoping, and privacy compliance. The strongest sign of mature data governance is that the organization can quickly and confidently answer, for any important data element, who owns it, how sensitive it is, how good it is, where the authoritative copy lives, and how long it will be kept. When those answers come readily and are backed by evidence, data is being managed as the asset it is; when they draw blank stares, the auditor has found a governance gap whose consequences ripple through the whole control environment, and one worth reporting even when the immediate symptom appeared in another audit area entirely. Treated as an asset, data repays the governance invested in it; treated as exhaust, it becomes a liability that surfaces at the worst possible moment.</p><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div><p>Keep the roles straight: the <b>data owner</b> (business) classifies data and authorizes access; the <b>data custodian</b> (IT) implements the controls; the <b>data steward</b> manages data quality and definitions. Ownership is a <b>business</b> accountability, never IT's by default. <b>Classification</b> exists so protection is proportionate to sensitivity — and it only helps if it is actually applied and drives handling rules.</p></div><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div><p>An auditor finds that access to a sensitive customer database is granted by the IT team on request, with no business owner reviewing whether the requester needs it, and the data carries no classification label. The finding is a <b>data governance gap</b>: without a named data owner and applied classification, access decisions lack business context and authority, and protection cannot be proportionate to sensitivity. The recommendation assigns ownership, classifies the data, and routes access approvals through the owner under least privilege.</p></div>"},
{"heading":"IT Resource Management","body":"<p><span class='keyterm'>IT resource management</span> is the set of processes by which the enterprise plans for, acquires, allocates, and optimizes the resources IT needs to deliver value — its people, its infrastructure and capacity, its applications, its information, and the money that funds them. From the auditor's seat, the question is whether resources are managed deliberately against demand and strategy, so that IT neither starves critical initiatives nor squanders investment on low-value activity. Resource management is one of COBIT's governance objectives (resource optimization), sitting alongside benefits realization and risk optimization as the trio the board must balance.</p><h3>Capacity and Performance Planning</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Capacity planning</span> ensures that IT resources — compute, storage, network, staff — are sufficient to meet current and forecast demand at agreed service levels, without the waste of large idle surpluses. The auditor evaluates whether capacity is planned proactively from business forecasts and monitored against thresholds, or managed reactively by responding to outages after they occur. Effective capacity management tracks utilization trends, models growth, and triggers procurement or optimization before shortfalls degrade service. A recurring weakness is capacity managed by firefighting: systems run to exhaustion, performance degrades, and emergency purchases follow — more costly and disruptive than planned provisioning. Capacity planning links to enterprise architecture (scalability is an architectural property) and to service management (it protects agreed service levels). The auditor looks for evidence that capacity data is collected, trended, and used in planning, and that business growth plans feed into IT provisioning. Capacity is not only about hardware: it includes software licensing (running out of licensed seats can halt a rollout), personnel capacity (an overloaded team is a bottleneck no server upgrade fixes), and service throughput. The auditor evaluates whether capacity management spans these dimensions or fixates on infrastructure alone.</p><p>Closely related is <span class='keyterm'>asset management</span>. An accurate inventory of IT assets — hardware, software, and licenses — is foundational to resource management, because you cannot optimize, secure, or budget for what you have not catalogued. The auditor evaluates whether an asset inventory exists, is kept current through the acquisition-to-disposal lifecycle, and reconciles to what is actually deployed. Software license management is a frequent weakness with real consequences: under-licensing exposes the organization to costly true-ups and legal action from vendor audits, while over-licensing wastes money on unused entitlements. Unmanaged assets also become security and cost liabilities — unknown devices are unpatched, and forgotten cloud or software subscriptions drain budget silently.</p><h3>IT Investment and Portfolio Management</h3><p>IT competes for finite funds, so the enterprise needs a disciplined way to choose which investments to make and to track whether they deliver. <span class='keyterm'>IT portfolio management</span> treats the collection of IT investments and assets as a portfolio to be balanced for value, risk, and alignment, much as a financial portfolio is managed. <span class='keyterm'>IT investment management</span> governs individual investment decisions through business cases, prioritization, funding, and benefits tracking. The auditor evaluates whether investments are selected against defined criteria tied to strategy (not by whoever lobbies hardest), whether a governance body such as the steering committee prioritizes and approves them, and — crucially — whether <span class='keyterm'>benefits realization</span> is tracked after delivery. The exam repeatedly stresses that value is not proven by delivering a project on time and budget; it is proven by comparing actual outcomes to the benefits the business case promised. An organization that approves investments but never checks whether promised benefits materialized cannot manage its portfolio for value, and the auditor treats absent benefits tracking as a significant governance gap.</p><p>Portfolio management also demands balance, not just individual project approval. A healthy portfolio mixes investments across categories — for instance keeping the lights on (mandatory maintenance), growing the business, and transforming it — so the organization does not sink everything into maintenance while starving innovation, or gamble everything on unproven transformation. The auditor evaluates whether the enterprise has visibility into its whole portfolio and its balance, whether investments are periodically re-evaluated (an approved project whose assumptions have collapsed should be stopped, not continued out of inertia — the sunk-cost trap), and whether there is a mechanism to retire or rationalize investments that no longer deliver. Chargeback or showback mechanisms, which attribute IT costs back to the business units that consume them, are a further control the auditor may assess: they make consumption visible and encourage business owners to weigh IT cost against value rather than treating IT as free.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Resource area</th><th>Management concern</th><th>What the auditor evaluates</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Capacity/infrastructure</td><td>Meet demand at service levels</td><td>Proactive planning vs. reactive firefighting</td></tr><tr><td>Financial/investment</td><td>Fund the right initiatives</td><td>Business cases, prioritization, benefits tracking</td></tr><tr><td>Human resources</td><td>Right skills, right numbers</td><td>Competency, succession, key-person risk</td></tr><tr><td>Applications/information</td><td>Rationalized, supported estate</td><td>Duplication, obsolescence, value delivery</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Value Delivery</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Value delivery</span> is the governance objective of ensuring IT delivers the promised benefits against strategy, on time and budget, and with the value being realized in practice. The auditor evaluates whether the enterprise defines what value means for each investment, measures it, and holds someone accountable for realizing it. Value is not the same as activity or spend; an IT department can be extremely busy and well-funded yet deliver little value if its work is not aligned to business priorities. The auditor connects value delivery back to alignment (Section 2) and to performance monitoring (Section 10): the balanced scorecard and benefits tracking are the instruments that make value visible. A useful audit lens is to ask, for the largest IT expenditures, what business outcome each was meant to produce and whether anyone can show that it did. Where the answer is a description of activity (\"we implemented the system\") rather than outcome (\"processing time fell by 30 percent as promised\"), value is being assumed rather than managed, and the auditor reports the gap between spend and demonstrated benefit.</p><h3>Human Resources and Competency</h3><p>People are IT's most important and most fragile resource. The auditor evaluates whether the organization has the right skills in the right numbers, manages <span class='keyterm'>competency</span> through training and development, and mitigates <span class='keyterm'>key-person (single-person) dependency</span> — the risk that a critical process is understood by only one individual whose departure or absence would cripple it. Controls here include documented procedures, cross-training, succession planning, and mandatory vacations or job rotation, which double as fraud-detection controls by forcing another person into a role. The auditor also considers HR-related security controls that support resource integrity: background screening on hire, clear role definitions, segregation of duties, and prompt access revocation on termination or transfer — a control whose failure leaves departed staff with live access. Over-reliance on contractors or a single vendor for critical skills is another resource risk, blurring the line into vendor management. The auditor also considers whether the organization plans its skills against its strategy: a shift toward new technologies the current workforce cannot support is a resource gap that must be closed by hiring, training, or sourcing before the strategy can succeed. Workforce retention is a governance concern too, because losing experienced staff destroys institutional knowledge and reintroduces key-person risk, so high turnover in a critical team is a signal the auditor notes. The auditor's summary judgment is whether IT resources — money, capacity, applications, and above all people — are planned against demand and strategy, optimized rather than merely consumed, and protected against the concentration and continuity risks that unmanaged resources create. Resource management ties the domain together: capacity connects to architecture and service levels, investment connects to governance and alignment, and human-resource controls connect to security and continuity — so weaknesses here rarely stay contained, and the auditor reports them with their downstream implications rather than as isolated inefficiencies. The central test is optimization against demand and strategy: are resources deployed where they create the most value, sized to real need, and protected against the concentration and continuity risks that neglect creates? Where the answer is yes and the evidence supports it, IT is resourced to deliver; where resources drift, unmeasured and unaligned, the auditor reports that the enterprise is spending on IT without governing what that spending buys. Resource optimization, benefits realization, and risk optimization are the three balanced objectives of IT governance, and this section supplies the first and much of the second — which is why resource-management weaknesses so often read, at root, as governance weaknesses in disguise. The auditor's role is to make that connection explicit, tracing an efficiency symptom back to the absent planning, prioritization, or accountability that allowed it.</p><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div><p><b>Value is proven by realized benefits, not by on-time/on-budget delivery.</b> If benefits are never tracked after a project, the enterprise cannot manage its portfolio for value. Capacity should be planned <b>proactively</b> from business forecasts, not managed by reacting to outages. <b>Key-person dependency</b> is a resource risk mitigated by cross-training, documentation, succession planning, and job rotation.</p></div><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div><p>An auditor finds the company approves IT projects with detailed business cases projecting cost savings, but no process ever compares actual results to those projections after go-live. The finding is <b>absent benefits realization</b>: without post-implementation measurement, management cannot know whether its IT investments delivered the promised value, so portfolio decisions are made on hope. The recommendation establishes benefits tracking with named owners who report realized value against each business case.</p></div>"},
{"heading":"IT Vendor Management","body":"<p><span class='keyterm'>IT vendor management</span> (third-party management) governs the relationships through which the enterprise obtains IT products and services from outside suppliers. Because outsourcing shifts execution but not accountability, vendor management is a control-rich area the exam probes heavily. The independent auditor evaluates whether third parties are selected with due diligence, bound by clear contracts, monitored against agreed service levels, and managed for the risk they introduce — including risks from the vendors' own vendors. The governing principle throughout is that the organization remains accountable to its customers and regulators for outsourced activities, so weak vendor oversight is the organization's finding, not merely the supplier's.</p><h3>Selection and Due Diligence</h3><p>Sound sourcing begins before any contract. Requirements are defined, then candidates are solicited — often through a <span class='keyterm'>request for proposal (RFP)</span> that states requirements and evaluation criteria so bids can be compared objectively (a request for information, RFI, gathers market information earlier; a request for quotation, RFQ, seeks pricing for defined goods). The auditor evaluates whether selection was competitive, criteria-based, and documented, or steered to a favored vendor without justification. <span class='keyterm'>Due diligence</span> then assesses each finalist's financial stability, technical capability, security posture, compliance history, and references, proportionate to the criticality of the service. The auditor checks that due diligence was performed and evidenced before commitment; onboarding a critical provider without vetting its security or viability is a control failure. For services touching sensitive data or core operations, due diligence should include reviewing independent assurance such as SOC reports or certifications, read for scope and exceptions rather than accepted at face value.</p><p>Sourcing decisions themselves warrant scrutiny. The choice to outsource — and where — is a governance decision with strategic, cost, and risk dimensions. <span class='keyterm'>Offshoring</span> to distant jurisdictions can lower cost but introduces data-residency, legal, language, time-zone, and geopolitical risks; <span class='keyterm'>nearshoring</span> and onshore options trade some cost savings for reduced friction. Cloud sourcing (obtaining infrastructure, platforms, or software as a service) shifts the operating model and the control boundary, so responsibility for controls must be explicitly divided between provider and customer — a division the customer often misunderstands, assuming the provider secures everything. The auditor evaluates whether the sourcing decision was made deliberately, with risks assessed and a business case, rather than by default or on price alone, and whether the resulting control-responsibility split is documented and understood. A recurring finding is a shadow arrangement — a business unit procuring an external service directly, bypassing IT and procurement governance — which escapes due diligence, contract review, and security assessment entirely.</p><h3>Contracts, SLAs, and the Agreement Stack</h3><p>The contract is the primary control instrument, and the auditor reads it for the terms that protect the organization. Chief among them is the <span class='keyterm'>service level agreement (SLA)</span> — the commitment defining measurable service targets (availability, response time, resolution time) and the remedies or penalties for missing them. The auditor distinguishes the SLA from two related agreements: an <span class='keyterm'>operating level agreement (OLA)</span> is internal, between teams within the organization that together support the external SLA; and an <span class='keyterm'>underpinning contract (UC)</span> is with a further external supplier whose performance the vendor depends on. An SLA promising four-hour resolution cannot be met if the underpinning contract with a subcontractor only guarantees next-business-day support — a mismatch the auditor looks for.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Agreement</th><th>Between</th><th>Purpose</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>SLA</td><td>Organization and external vendor</td><td>Measurable service targets and remedies</td></tr><tr><td>OLA</td><td>Internal teams</td><td>Internal support that underpins the SLA</td></tr><tr><td>UC (underpinning)</td><td>Vendor and its supplier</td><td>External support the vendor relies on</td></tr></tbody></table><p>Beyond service levels, the auditor looks for key contract terms: a <span class='keyterm'>right-to-audit clause</span> allowing the organization (or its auditors) to examine the vendor's controls; security and confidentiality obligations and data-protection terms; breach-notification requirements; ownership of data and intellectual property; <span class='keyterm'>exit and transition provisions</span> ensuring data return and continuity if the relationship ends (guarding against lock-in); liability and indemnification; compliance with applicable law; and limits on subcontracting. Missing a right-to-audit clause, or vague exit terms, are recurring findings because they leave the organization unable to verify controls or to leave cleanly.</p><p>The auditor also weighs the pricing and performance-incentive structure, because it shapes vendor behavior. A contract that pays for effort or volume rewards busyness; one that pays against outcomes and enforces SLA penalties rewards results. The auditor evaluates whether the SLA metrics are objective, measurable, and actually measured (an SLA no one reports against is unenforceable), whether penalties are meaningful enough to change behavior, and whether the contract provides for renegotiation as needs evolve. For long-term or critical relationships, the auditor checks that governance is defined within the contract itself — relationship managers, review cadences, escalation paths, and dispute resolution — so the relationship is actively managed rather than left dormant until something breaks.</p><h3>Ongoing Monitoring and Extended Risk</h3><p>Vendor management does not end at signing. The auditor evaluates whether performance is monitored against the SLA with real metrics and periodic reviews, whether issues are escalated and remediated, and whether the vendor's ongoing financial and security health is reassessed over the relationship's life. A vendor vetted once and never revisited can degrade unnoticed. Two extended risks deserve attention. <span class='keyterm'>Fourth-party (and supply-chain) risk</span> is the risk from the vendor's own subcontractors — the organization's data may be handled by parties it never directly assessed, so the auditor checks whether the contract controls subcontracting and whether the vendor manages its own supply chain. <span class='keyterm'>Concentration risk</span> arises when too much depends on a single provider, so its failure would be catastrophic. Where services are sourced externally, the auditor also confirms responsibility for controls is clearly divided and that the organization retains oversight of the controls it depends on, rather than assuming the provider handles everything. A structured practice here is <span class='keyterm'>vendor risk tiering</span>: classifying suppliers by criticality and data sensitivity so that oversight effort is proportionate — a provider hosting the core transaction system warrants far deeper and more frequent scrutiny than a stationery supplier. The auditor evaluates whether such tiering exists and drives the depth of due diligence and monitoring, because treating all vendors identically either wastes effort on trivial ones or, more dangerously, under-scrutinizes critical ones. Business continuity extends into the relationship as well: the auditor evaluates whether the organization has assessed the impact of a critical vendor failing — insolvency, a major breach, or a prolonged outage — and whether contingency exists in the form of an alternative provider, an in-house fallback, or at minimum a plan and the data needed to execute it. A dependency on a single vendor with no continuity plan is a concentration risk that a well-drafted SLA does nothing to mitigate, because penalties do not restore a service that has collapsed. The auditor's overall judgment is whether third parties are governed across the full lifecycle — selection, due diligence, contracting, monitoring, and exit — with accountability firmly retained by the organization, or whether outsourcing has been treated as a way to hand off risk that in fact remains the organization's own. The tests are practical: obtain the vendor inventory and confirm critical suppliers are identified and tiered; sample contracts for SLAs, right-to-audit, security, and exit terms; review whether performance is actually measured and reviewed; and check whether independent assurance over each critical vendor's controls is obtained and read for scope and exceptions. Where the enterprise cannot show it knows which vendors are critical, cannot verify their controls, and cannot exit or continue operating if one fails, the auditor reports that third-party risk is inadequately governed — an increasingly consequential finding as organizations depend ever more on external providers and their extended supply chains. The governing principle bears repeating because the exam returns to it relentlessly: you can outsource the work, but never the accountability. That single idea, applied consistently across selection, contracting, monitoring, and exit, is the lens through which the auditor evaluates every vendor arrangement it encounters. And because modern enterprises rely on layered chains of providers, the auditor extends the same discipline downstream — asking not only about the vendor, but about the vendor's vendors — so that the accountability retained at the top is matched by visibility all the way down the chain that ultimately handles the organization's data and delivers its services. A right-to-audit clause that stops at the first vendor, while that vendor freely subcontracts to unassessed parties, offers only the illusion of oversight, and the auditor probes for exactly that gap.</p><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div><p><b>Outsourcing transfers execution, not accountability</b> — the organization stays responsible for outsourced services. Distinguish <b>SLA</b> (with the external vendor), <b>OLA</b> (internal teams), and <b>UC</b> (the vendor's own supplier). Always look for a <b>right-to-audit clause</b> and clear <b>exit/transition</b> terms. <b>Fourth-party risk</b> is the risk from your vendor's subcontractors.</p></div><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div><p>An auditor reviews a contract with a critical service provider and finds a well-drafted SLA but no right-to-audit clause and no defined exit provisions for returning data if the contract ends. The finding is that the organization <b>cannot independently verify the vendor's controls and would struggle to exit</b>, creating oversight and lock-in risk. The recommendation adds right-to-audit and transition clauses and, in the interim, obtains independent assurance (such as a scoped SOC report) over the vendor's control environment.</p></div>"},
{"heading":"IT Performance Monitoring and Reporting","body":"<p><span class='keyterm'>Performance monitoring and reporting</span> is how the enterprise knows whether IT is actually delivering against its objectives, and it is the feedback loop that makes governance more than a one-time direction-setting exercise. Recall COBIT's governance cycle of Evaluate, Direct, and <em>Monitor</em>: monitoring closes the loop by feeding results back so direction can be corrected. The auditor evaluates whether IT performance is measured against meaningful objectives, reported honestly to those who can act, and used to drive improvement — or whether metrics are collected for show, chosen because they are easy rather than important, and never influence a decision.</p><h3>Metrics: KPIs and KRIs</h3><p>The core instruments are indicators. A <span class='keyterm'>key performance indicator (KPI)</span> measures progress toward an objective — for example, percentage of changes implemented without incident, system availability against target, or mean time to resolve. A <span class='keyterm'>key risk indicator (KRI)</span> provides early warning that risk exposure is rising — for example, growth in unpatched systems or in privileged accounts. Good indicators share qualities the auditor tests: they are aligned to objectives (they measure what matters, not merely what is easy to count), clearly defined, owned, based on reliable data, and paired with targets or thresholds that make a result actionable. A metric with no target answers no question; a target no one owns triggers no action. The auditor watches for <span class='keyterm'>vanity metrics</span> that look impressive but measure nothing important, and for the opposite failure — critical objectives with no measure at all, so problems stay invisible until they become incidents. A useful test of a metric set is whether the metrics could ever deliver bad news: a dashboard that structurally cannot show a problem is measuring the wrong things. The auditor also checks for balance between efficiency measures (cost, throughput) and effectiveness measures (did the output achieve its purpose), because optimizing efficiency alone can degrade effectiveness — faster ticket closure means nothing if the underlying problems recur.</p><h3>Metric Design and Data Integrity</h3><p>Beyond individual metrics, the auditor evaluates the discipline of the measurement system. Metrics should be <span class='keyterm'>SMART</span> in spirit — specific, measurable, achievable, relevant, and time-bound — and each should have a defined calculation so results are comparable over time and cannot be quietly redefined to look better. A subtle risk the exam probes is <span class='keyterm'>gaming</span>: when people are measured and rewarded on a metric, they optimize the metric, sometimes at the expense of the real objective it was meant to represent. Measuring developers on lines of code, or a help desk on call volume, invites behavior that inflates the number while harming the outcome. The auditor considers whether the metric set is robust against gaming and whether it captures outcomes, not just easily manipulated proxies. Underpinning everything is <span class='keyterm'>data integrity</span>: a metric is only as trustworthy as its source. Where figures are compiled manually, sourced from systems of uncertain reliability, or entered by the same people whose performance they reflect, the auditor treats the reporting itself as a control risk and tests how the numbers are produced.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Indicator/tool</th><th>Answers</th><th>Auditor's concern</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>KPI</td><td>Are we meeting objectives?</td><td>Aligned, defined, owned, targeted</td></tr><tr><td>KRI</td><td>Is risk exposure rising?</td><td>Thresholds trigger timely action</td></tr><tr><td>Benchmark</td><td>How do we compare to others/past?</td><td>Comparable basis, honest use</td></tr><tr><td>Balanced scorecard</td><td>Are all perspectives balanced?</td><td>Links metrics back to strategy</td></tr><tr><td>Maturity model</td><td>How capable is the process?</td><td>Assessed objectively, drives improvement</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Benchmarking and the Balanced Scorecard</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Benchmarking</span> compares the organization's performance against a reference point — industry peers, recognized standards, or its own past results — to reveal where it lags or leads and to set realistic targets. The auditor evaluates whether benchmarks use a genuinely comparable basis (comparing against dissimilar organizations misleads) and whether results actually inform targets and improvement rather than being filed away. The <span class='keyterm'>IT balanced scorecard</span>, introduced in Section 2, is the reporting framework that keeps measurement balanced across perspectives — corporate contribution, user/customer orientation, operational excellence, and future orientation — so IT is not judged solely on technical uptime while business value goes unmeasured. The auditor checks that the scorecard cascades from strategy, that each measure ties to an objective, and that it is populated with real data and reviewed by management, closing the loop back to alignment.</p><h3>Maturity Models</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Maturity models</span> assess how capable and consistent a process is, typically on a scale from ad hoc to optimized. The widely referenced five-level pattern runs from <span class='keyterm'>initial</span> (unpredictable, ad hoc), to <span class='keyterm'>managed/repeatable</span> (basic processes exist), to <span class='keyterm'>defined</span> (standardized and documented), to <span class='keyterm'>quantitatively managed</span> (measured and controlled with data), to <span class='keyterm'>optimizing</span> (continuous improvement). Maturity models let the organization assess current capability, set a realistic target level, and plan improvement — and they give the auditor an objective vocabulary for describing process capability rather than a subjective \"good/bad.\" The auditor evaluates whether maturity assessments are performed honestly (self-assessment tends to flatter), whether an appropriate target is set (not every process needs the highest level — that costs more than it returns for low-risk processes), and whether the assessment drives an improvement plan rather than sitting as a score. Maturity assessment pairs naturally with benchmarking: knowing that a peer group operates a process at a higher maturity level, or that an industry standard expects one, gives the organization an external reference for where to aim. The auditor looks for the assessment to be repeated periodically so progress (or regression) is visible over time.</p><h3>Reporting That Drives Action</h3><p>Measurement is worthless if the results do not reach decision-makers in a usable form. The auditor evaluates the reporting chain: is performance reported to the steering committee and board at a defined cadence, tailored to the audience (executives need summarized trends and exceptions, not raw operational data), and honest about shortfalls? A recurring weakness is reporting that highlights successes and buries failures, so governance bodies believe all is well while problems fester. Another is reporting with no consequence — dashboards no one reviews, red indicators that trigger no action. The auditor also assesses data integrity: metrics are only as trustworthy as their sources, so if utilization or availability figures are manually compiled and unverified, the reporting itself is a risk. The overall judgment is whether performance monitoring is a live governance control — meaningful measures, honest reporting, and decisions and improvements that actually follow — or a ritual that produces numbers no one uses. Because monitoring closes the governance loop, its weakness means the board is steering IT without reliable feedback, which the auditor treats as a serious governance concern.</p><p>The auditor's evaluation of monitoring therefore runs the full chain: Are the right things measured, aligned to objectives and balanced across efficiency and effectiveness? Are the metrics well-defined, owned, target-bearing, resistant to gaming, and sourced from trustworthy data? Are results reported to the right audiences at the right cadence, honestly including the bad news? And — the decisive test — do the results actually drive decisions and improvements, closing the loop back to direction? Where every link holds, monitoring is a genuine governance control that lets the board correct course before small problems become crises. Where links break — vanity metrics, buried failures, dashboards no one acts on — the auditor reports that the enterprise measures without managing, and that its governance loop is open. As across the domain, the conclusion rests on observed behavior and evidence: not whether reports exist, but whether they are meaningful, honest, and consequential. Monitoring is the discipline that turns governance from a periodic ceremony into a continuous, self-correcting system, and its quality is a direct measure of how seriously the board's oversight responsibility is actually discharged. In practice the auditor tests this by tracing a reported metric to a decision: did a red indicator ever prompt a documented action, was a missed target ever investigated and corrected? Where such traces exist, monitoring is alive; where reports flow up and nothing flows back, the loop is decorative, and the auditor says so plainly, because a governance body that receives information but never acts on it is not exercising oversight regardless of how polished its dashboards appear. The auditor's conclusion on monitoring, then, is not about the sophistication of the tooling but about whether measurement demonstrably drives the direction-setting and correction that make governance a living system rather than an annual formality.</p><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div><p>Good metrics are <b>aligned to objectives, defined, owned, and paired with targets/thresholds</b> that make results actionable. <b>KPIs</b> measure objective achievement; <b>KRIs</b> give early warning of rising risk. The <b>balanced scorecard</b> keeps IT measured across perspectives, not just uptime. <b>Maturity models</b> describe process capability objectively and should drive an improvement plan, with the target level matched to the process's risk.</p></div><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div><p>An auditor finds IT reports a dashboard of green indicators to the board every quarter, but the metrics are all technical (server uptime, tickets closed) and none measure whether IT is delivering business value or where risk is rising. The finding is that <b>monitoring is not aligned to objectives</b>: the board receives reassuring but uninformative data and cannot govern effectively. The recommendation introduces balanced, objective-linked KPIs and KRIs with targets, honest exception reporting, and evidence that results drive corrective action.</p></div>"},
{"heading":"Quality Assurance and Quality Management of IT","body":"<p><span class='keyterm'>Quality management</span> is the enterprise-wide discipline of ensuring that IT products and services consistently meet defined requirements and stakeholder expectations, and of improving the processes that produce them. The auditor evaluates whether quality is built into how IT works — planned, assured, controlled, and continually improved — or whether it is left to chance and inspected for only at the end, when defects are expensive to fix. Quality management is closely tied to the control and performance themes of this domain: a mature quality system produces predictable, repeatable outcomes, which is exactly the property that makes controls reliable.</p><h3>Quality Assurance versus Quality Control</h3><p>The exam expects a clean distinction between two related activities. <span class='keyterm'>Quality assurance (QA)</span> is <em>process-oriented and preventive</em>: it establishes and verifies that the right processes, standards, and methods are in place so that quality is produced by design — reviews of whether the development methodology is being followed, whether standards are applied, whether the process itself is sound. <span class='keyterm'>Quality control (QC)</span> is <em>product-oriented and detective</em>: it inspects and tests the actual deliverables to find defects — testing software, checking outputs against specifications. QA asks \"are we doing the right things the right way?\"; QC asks \"did the thing we produced meet the requirement?\" Both are needed: QC without QA catches defects but never fixes the process that keeps producing them, while QA without QC assumes a good process guarantees a good product without verifying. The auditor evaluates whether both exist and, importantly, whether the QA function has enough <span class='keyterm'>independence</span> from the development teams it reviews to report problems candidly — a QA group reporting to the project manager it assesses has a conflict analogous to the auditor's own independence concerns. It helps to place both within the broader concept of <span class='keyterm'>quality management</span>, which encompasses four activities: quality planning (defining what quality means and how it will be achieved for a given product or service), quality assurance (the process-oriented prevention just described), quality control (the product-oriented inspection), and quality improvement (systematically raising the capability of the process over time). The auditor evaluates whether all four are present, because organizations frequently have QC and little else — they test the product but neither plan for quality up front nor improve the process that produces defects.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Aspect</th><th>Quality assurance (QA)</th><th>Quality control (QC)</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Focus</td><td>Process</td><td>Product/deliverable</td></tr><tr><td>Nature</td><td>Preventive</td><td>Detective</td></tr><tr><td>Question</td><td>Are we doing things right?</td><td>Did we produce the right thing?</td></tr><tr><td>Example</td><td>Verify the SDLC is followed</td><td>Test the software for defects</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Quality Management Systems and Standards</h3><p>A <span class='keyterm'>quality management system (QMS)</span> is the formal structure of policies, processes, and procedures an organization uses to direct its quality activities. <span class='keyterm'>ISO 9001</span> is the internationally recognized standard for a QMS, built on principles including customer focus, leadership, engagement of people, a process approach, evidence-based decision-making, and — central to the whole philosophy — <span class='keyterm'>continual improvement</span>. Certification to ISO 9001 signals that an organization operates a documented, audited quality system, though as with any certification the auditor reads scope and treats it as evidence of a system's existence rather than proof of every outcome's quality. The <span class='keyterm'>Plan-Do-Check-Act (PDCA)</span> cycle underlies most quality frameworks: plan an improvement, do it on a small scale, check the results, and act to standardize what worked or adjust what did not — an iterative loop the auditor recognizes as the engine of continual improvement. A closely related discipline is <span class='keyterm'>root-cause analysis</span>: when a defect or incident occurs, the mature organization does not merely fix the symptom but investigates why it happened and addresses the underlying cause so it cannot recur. Techniques such as the five-whys or fishbone (cause-and-effect) diagrams support this. The auditor evaluates whether the organization performs root-cause analysis on significant defects and incidents and whether the resulting corrective actions are tracked to completion — because catching and patching the same defect repeatedly, without ever asking why it keeps appearing, is the signature of a quality system that lacks a genuine improvement loop. Preventive action — acting on a potential problem before it materializes — completes the picture, and the auditor looks for evidence that lessons feed forward into future work rather than being relearned each time.</p><h3>Process Improvement and Maturity: CMMI</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Capability Maturity Model Integration (CMMI)</span> is a process-improvement framework, originally focused on software development and now broader, that describes the maturity of an organization's processes across the familiar five levels — <span class='keyterm'>initial</span> (ad hoc, unpredictable), <span class='keyterm'>managed</span> (processes planned and tracked at the project level), <span class='keyterm'>defined</span> (standardized organization-wide), <span class='keyterm'>quantitatively managed</span> (measured and statistically controlled), and <span class='keyterm'>optimizing</span> (focused on continual improvement). CMMI gives the organization a roadmap: assess current capability, target an appropriate level, and improve deliberately toward it. The auditor evaluates whether process improvement is pursued systematically using such a model, whether the target maturity is proportionate to the process's importance (chasing the highest level everywhere wastes resources), and whether improvement is evidenced by real process change rather than a certificate on the wall. Related bodies of practice — such as Six Sigma for defect reduction and Total Quality Management for organization-wide quality culture — pursue the same goal of consistent, improving outcomes, and the auditor need not master each but should recognize the common thread of measured, continual improvement. A related idea worth recognizing is the <span class='keyterm'>cost of quality</span>: the total cost of quality comprises prevention and appraisal costs (investing in getting it right and checking it) plus the cost of failures (internal rework and external defects reaching customers). The insight the exam expects is that investing in prevention through good QA and process discipline is generally far cheaper than paying for failures after the fact — a defect caught in design costs a fraction of the same defect caught in production. An organization that skimps on prevention to save money usually pays more in rework and reputational damage, and the auditor frames quality investment in these terms when evaluating whether management's approach is economically sound as well as controlled.</p><h3>What the Auditor Concludes</h3><p>Bringing quality management under the audit lens, the auditor asks: Does a defined quality system exist with owned processes and standards? Are QA (process) and QC (product) both performed, with QA independent enough to be candid? Is quality measured, and are defects analyzed for root cause so the process improves rather than the same errors recurring? Is there a genuine continual-improvement mechanism — PDCA, a maturity roadmap — that changes how work is done? Where these are present and evidenced, IT is likely to produce predictable, requirement-meeting outcomes, which supports control reliability across every other area of this domain. Where they are absent — quality inspected for only at the end, no process discipline, no improvement loop — the auditor expects to see recurring defects, unpredictable delivery, and weak controls, and reports the quality-management gap as a root cause. As throughout Domain 2, the auditor's stance is evidence-based and independent: a quality program is credited for what it demonstrably does to prevent and detect defects and improve processes, not for the aspirations printed in its manual. The most telling audit evidence is the trend line: are defect rates, rework, and recurring incidents falling over time as the process matures, or are the same problems reappearing release after release? A falling trend, backed by root-cause analysis and tracked corrective actions, is proof that quality management is real; a flat or rising trend, whatever the certifications on the wall, tells the auditor the improvement loop is not turning. Quality management thus closes Domain 2 on the same note it opened: governance and management are judged not by their documents but by whether they produce reliable, improving, requirement-meeting outcomes that the enterprise — and its auditor — can trust. A quality system that plans for quality, assures the process, controls the product, and improves relentlessly gives the auditor confidence that the controls it relies on elsewhere will behave predictably; one that inspects at the end and never learns leaves every downstream control resting on shaky, unrepeatable ground. That connection — from process quality to control reliability to the trustworthiness of the whole environment — is why the auditor treats quality management not as a peripheral concern but as a foundation on which much of the assurance in this domain ultimately depends.</p><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div><p><b>QA is process-oriented and preventive</b> (\"are we doing things right?\"); <b>QC is product-oriented and detective</b> (\"did we produce the right thing?\"). Both are needed, and QA should be <b>independent</b> of the teams it reviews. <b>ISO 9001</b> defines a QMS built on continual improvement; <b>CMMI</b> describes process maturity across five levels and should drive real improvement, not just certification.</p></div><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div><p>An auditor finds the organization tests software thoroughly before release (strong QC) but the same categories of defect recur release after release, because no one examines why the development process keeps producing them. The finding is <b>QC without effective QA and process improvement</b>: defects are caught but the process that creates them is never fixed, so cost and rework persist. The recommendation adds independent process assurance and a root-cause-driven continual-improvement loop so recurring defects are eliminated at their source.</p></div>"}
];
